# Performance, memory, and concurrency

## Evidence before optimization

- NEVER claim a performance improvement without a representative benchmark, profiler trace, load test, or measured production signal.
- Establish baseline, workload, dataset, hardware/runtime, warm-up, sample count, percentile, variance, and acceptance threshold.
- Optimize the system bottleneck, not a visually complex function.
- Preserve a readable reference implementation when an optimized implementation is materially harder to verify.

## Allocation and data movement

- In measured hot paths, prefer zero-copy or bounded-copy designs, contiguous memory, streaming, slices/views, buffer reuse, batching, and preallocation.
- NEVER introduce object pooling without a profile showing allocation/GC pressure and tests proving correct reset, ownership, and lifetime behavior.
- Avoid repeated parse/serialize cycles, intermediate collections, string concatenation in loops, unnecessary boxing, and full-buffer materialization.
- Bound every queue, buffer, cache, batch, recursion depth, fan-out, and in-flight operation.
- Apply backpressure instead of permitting unbounded memory growth.
- Document ownership and lifetime for borrowed buffers, views, pooled objects, and native resources.

## Algorithms and mechanical sympathy

- Select algorithms by workload shape, asymptotic cost, constants, memory locality, branch behavior, vectorization opportunity, contention, and I/O pattern.
- For every performance-critical public function, include a concise complexity note covering time, auxiliary space, dominant allocations, and relevant worst case.
- Prefer sequential contiguous access over pointer-heavy structures when behavior and benchmarks support it.
- Avoid false sharing, lock convoys, oversubscription, excessive context switching, and unnecessary cross-NUMA traffic in systems where these effects matter.

## Concurrency

- Prefer ownership transfer, immutable messages, structured concurrency, actors, channels, or task groups over shared mutable state.
- NEVER add lock-free code without a documented memory model, linearization points, ABA analysis where relevant, stress tests, and benchmark evidence.
- Define cancellation, deadlines, shutdown order, partial failure, and resource cleanup.
- Never block an event-loop or async executor with synchronous I/O or unbounded CPU work.
- Avoid coarse locks in hot paths; do not replace a correct lock with a more complex primitive without evidence.

## Performance acceptance

- Define budgets for latency percentiles, throughput, CPU, memory, allocations, I/O, startup, and payload size as relevant.
- Add regression tests or benchmark thresholds for critical paths.
- Performance changes MUST preserve functional equivalence, security invariants, observability, and failure semantics.
